Hi there,

It looks like this SDK doesn't support multiple geolocations whereas the API does. [The code](https://github.com/algolia/algoliasearch-django/blob/master/src/models.py#L155-L159) wouldn't be too difficult to adapt, something like that would work:
```python
def _validate_geoloc(geo):
    assert set(geo) == {'lat', 'lng'}, 'Invalid geolocation format, requires "lat" and "lng" keys, only.'
if isinstance(loc, tuple):
    tmp['_geoloc'] = {'lat': loc[0], 'lng': loc[1]}
elif isinstance(loc, dict):
    _validate_geoloc(loc)
    tmp['_geoloc'] = loc
elif isinstance(loc, list):
    [_validate_geoloc(geo) for geo in loc]
    tmp['_geoloc'] = loc
```

Do you accept PRs for this project?

As decided by the poll in slack (https://empirehacking.slack.com/archives/C3PTWK7UM/p1494966837390179, https://gist.github.com/yan/265a14ad90c2715fac31238c5cae95cb), we will use an `@variadic` decorator for marking user defined function models as taking a variable number of arguments. This will cause the function to take a single argument, which is a generator object for the arguments to the function.

```
# 1 ------------------------------------------------
# Option 1, "@variadic" attribute on the model itself, and it takes a single
# parameter which acts as an iterator for all functions. Calling next() on the
# args object gets you arguments. Invoking vararg and constant arity functions
# is identical.

from manticore import variadic

@variadic
def printf(state, args):
    fmt = next(args)
    pass
@m.hook(printfaddr)
def hk(state):
    state.invoke_model(printf)
def strcmp(state, arg1, arg2):
    pass
@m.hook(strcmpaddr)
def hk(state):
    state.invoke_model(strcmp)
```

