@wisechengyi left a [comment](https://github.com/pantsbuild/pants/pull/6413#discussion_r213868228) on #6413:

> `stable_json_hash` is essentially hashing `json_str` which I am guessing is a byte string (e.g. `b'123'` instead of a str like `'123'`)...so the assert would look something like: `self.assertEqual(b'{"a":3}', get_json_str({'a': 3}))`.

We test the result of `stable_json_sha1()` in #6413, but the testing currently looks like `self.assertEqual(stable_json_sha1([{'a': 3}]), '8f4e36849a0b8fbe9c4a822c80fbee047c65458a')`, which isn't super debuggable if the assertion fails. If we split out the `json.dumps()` and the `hash_all()` calls in the body of `stable_json_hash()`, we could test the json encoding specifically, and then the hashing separately -- this would make it much easier to debug failing test cases, should we ever want to change the implementation of our json encoding (as we did in #6413).

