In upgrading a codebase to v2.2, I've noticed that pybind now cares about l-value references matching in constructors. So this used to work:

```cpp
#include <pybind11/pybind11.h>
namespace py = pybind11;

struct Test {
    Test(int &i) {};
};

PYBIND11_PLUGIN(sample) {
    py::module m("sample", "");
    py::class_<Test>(m,"Test")
        .def(py::init<int>());
    return m.ptr();
}
```

But now gives an error unless changed to this:
```cpp
        .def(py::init<int&>());
```

Which is much better, but should be mentioned in the upgrade guide to save others time figuring out the new build failure with a slightly cryptic error message.

PS: `PYBIND11_MODULE` and `python -m pybind11 --includes` are both nice for quick examples like this, I actually used the latter to make the include line that I used after switching back to 2.1 in my venv.

